Nuclear South Korea nuclear power generation to reach 29.8GW by 2035 report shows Power Engineering International Aug 06, 2025 Share Image by Markus Distelrath from Pixabay Nuclear power generation in South Korea is forecast to reach 222.7TWh in 2035, registering a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 2.4% during 2024-35. This is according to data and analytics company GlobalData’s latest report, South Korea Power Market Outlook to 2035, Update 2025. South Korea relies solely on domestic production for its electricity needs, as it lacks interconnections with neighbouring countries and does not engage in the import or export of electricity. The nation’s capacity to manage domestic electricity demand effectively is attributed to its substantial nuclear power generation infrastructure. In 2022, the nation reversed a policy to phase out nuclear energy and positioned it as a pivotal element of its energy strategy. Against this backdrop, GlobalData’s report predicts nuclear power capacity to reach 29.8GW by 2035. Have you read?Why scarcity is a myth and opportunity abounds for nuclear’s workforce strategyGermany’s nuclear u-turn and its continental ripple effects Currently, South Korea has 25 active reactors and four upcoming reactors under construction. Nuclear power contributes to meeting nearly one-third of the country’s electricity consumption. Attaurrahman Ojindaram Saibasan, senior power analyst at GlobalData, commented in a let adslot; adslot = '/' + gamAccount + '/' + sitePath; googletag.defineSlot(adslot, [[200,200],[300,250],[336,280]], 'side-block-top_block-advert-block_bb4b738d4613c6e84da59a9b8d0bccbe') .defineSizeMapping(mapping) .setCollapseEmptyDiv(true) .setTargeting('pos', 'side-block-top') .setTargeting('page', 'home') .addService(googletag.pubads()); googletag.display('side-block-top_block-advert-block_bb4b738d4613c6e84da59a9b8d0bccbe'); }); Trending this ,"post-excerpt":{"active":false,"length":"75","keep_format":false,"words":false},"thumbnail":{"act